[
    {
        "content": "<p>Let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> be a 2-category. Then there is a wide, locally-full sub-2-category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>j</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>⊆</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Adj(C) \\subseteq C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>, whose 1-morphisms are those 1-morphisms of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> which have a right adjoint in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>The construction <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>j</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C \\mapsto Adj(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is an endofunctor of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>C</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">2Cat</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>, and the inclusion <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>j</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Adj(C) \\to C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> makes this into a co-pointed endofunctor. I think it's even <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/well-pointed+endofunctor\">co-well-pointed</a>. However, I don't think that this co-well-pointed endofunctor is a comonad.</p>\n<p>This is a little weird. On the one hand I tend to think of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>j</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C \\mapsto Adj(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> as an \"intrinsically interesting construction\". On the other hand, I tend to think of endofunctors which are not co/monads as \"technical tools\" --surely any endofunctor worth its salt will have the decency to arise from some more fundamental adjunction, and thus be a co/monad, right? So I guess I'm wondering</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>Is there some other construction <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>f</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>o</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C \\mapsto foo(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">oo</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, related to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>j</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C \\mapsto Adj(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>,  which is more fundamental (and which perhaps is a co/monad or arises from some adjunction)? Whenever I see <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>j</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C \\mapsto Adj(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, should I really be thinking about <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>f</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>o</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C \\mapsto foo(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">oo</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>?</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>If not, then does <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>j</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C \\mapsto Adj(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> have a bit more structure than being a co-well-pointed endofunctor, which might make me feel a bit more \"at ease\" with this construction?</p>\n</li>\n</ol>",
        "id": 290688732,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1658680215
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For instance, one construction which might be relevant is the construction which turns <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> into the double category whose horizontal part is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> and whose vertical part is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>j</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Adj(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> (with the \"obvious\" squares). I'm not sure if this construction has better formal properties than <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>j</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C \\mapsto Adj(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 290688836,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1658680399
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, I must say I disagree with your opinion about endofunctors.  I think the world is littered with endofunctors that are not monads or comonads.</p>",
        "id": 290689985,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1658682106
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But it is possible to decompose <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rm Adj</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Adj</span></span></span></span></span> (or something equivalent to it) into a composite of other functors in a way that might be illuminating.  For instance, consider the composite <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow><mo>∘</mo><mi>H</mi><mo>∘</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\rm Comp}\\circ H \\circ \\rm Sq</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Comp</span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Sq</span></span></span></span></span> where:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi><mo>:</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rm Sq : 2Cat \\to Dbl</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Sq</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">2Cat</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Dbl</span></span></span></span></span> constructs the double category of squares (= quintets) in a 2-category.</li>\n<li><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H : \\rm Dbl \\to Dbl</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Dbl</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Dbl</span></span></span></span></span> constructs the horizontal opposite of a double category.</li>\n<li><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>→</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rm Comp : Dbl\\to 2Cat</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Comp</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Dbl</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">2Cat</span></span></span></span></span> constructs the 2-category of <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/companion%20pairs\">[[companion pairs]]</a> in a double category.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The composite <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow><mo>∘</mo><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\rm Comp}\\circ H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Comp</span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span> constructs the 2-category of <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/conjunctions\">[[conjunctions]]</a> in a double category, and a conjunction in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\rm Sq}(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Sq</span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is precisely an adjunction in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>.  So this composite constructs the 2-category of adjunctions in a 2-category.  This is biequivalent to your <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\rm Adj}(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Adj</span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, but includes the whole adjunction as data, rather than its mere existence as a property.</p>\n<p>In addition, we have an adjunction <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi><mo>⊣</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rm Sq \\dashv Comp</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Sq</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Comp</span></span></span></span></span>, so the composite <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>∘</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rm Comp \\circ Sq</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Comp</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Sq</span></span></span></span></span> is a monad (though it is biequivalent to the identity).  So this modified version of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rm Adj</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Adj</span></span></span></span></span> is a \"twist\" (<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span>) away from being a monad.</p>",
        "id": 290690343,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1658682594
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Nice!</p>",
        "id": 290690490,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1658682792
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh that <em>is</em> very nice!</p>",
        "id": 290691010,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1658683523
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276777\">@Mike Shulman</span>  I've had trouble finding an actual reference for the adjunction <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>q</mi><mo>⊣</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Sq \\dashv Comp</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">Sq</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span> -- is this in the literature somewhere?</p>",
        "id": 290691066,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1658683606
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>While I'm at it -- in the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-categorical setting, Gaitsgory and Rozenblyum conjectured that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Sq</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">Sq</span></span></span></span> is fully faithful, but I don't know a reference for this in the strict setting even. Do you?</p>",
        "id": 290691079,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1658683654
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(I also don't know a reference for the <em>left</em> adjoint of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Sq</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">Sq</span></span></span></span>, which is related to the Gray tensor product, but this is taking me increasingly further afield!)</p>",
        "id": 290691145,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1658683758
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No, I don't know a reference for that adjunction.</p>",
        "id": 290691149,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1658683773
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We discussed the putative full-faithfulness of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rm Sq</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Sq</span></span></span></span></span> <a href=\"https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2021/09/weakly_globular_double_categor.html#c060769\">here</a>.  I don't think I have anything to add to that.</p>",
        "id": 290691239,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1658683895
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh you're right -- we've talked about this before!</p>",
        "id": 290691284,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1658683928
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right -- I think my takeaway from that discussion was that if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Sq</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">Sq</span></span></span></span> is fully faithful, then it's only when you take the domain of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Sq</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">Sq</span></span></span></span> to be (Rezk-complete) <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\infty,2)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>-categories (or maybe <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(m,2)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>-categories for large enough <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">m</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span></span></span></span>).</p>",
        "id": 290691322,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1658684032
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277991\">Tim Campion</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/the.202-category.20of.20adjoints/near/290691066\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span>  I've had trouble finding an actual reference for the adjunction <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>q</mi><mo>⊣</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Sq \\dashv Comp</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">Sq</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span> -- is this in the literature somewhere?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>There is Theorem 1.7 in Grandis–Paré's <a href=\"http://www.numdam.org/item/?id=CTGDC_2004__45_3_193_0\">Adjoints for double categories</a>.</p>",
        "id": 292593228,
        "sender_full_name": "David Kern",
        "timestamp": 1660056705
    }
]